This is a strong v0.1. The bones are good.

The main thing breaking it is not the architecture — it’s the pasted typography. You’ve got smart quotes and a few Unicode punctuation characters in places React/JS will reject.

What’s wrong

You pasted code with:
	•	“ ” instead of "
	•	‘ ’ instead of '
	•	… or odd dash characters in some text contexts
	•	[…filtered, ...] using a smart/bracket variant instead of normal JS [...]
	•	CSS custom property typing in inline style that TypeScript may complain about

So the app concept is good, but the code needs to be de-corrupted into plain ASCII JS/TSX.

⸻

Biggest fixes

1. Imports

Use normal quotes:

import { useState, useEffect } from "react";

2. Arrays/objects

Every string needs plain quotes:

const BODY_ZONES = [
  { id: "head", label: "Head", cx: 200, cy: 52 },
  { id: "neck", label: "Neck", cx: 200, cy: 90 },
];

3. Broken spread line

This line is invalid as pasted:

return […filtered, { zone: activeZone, type: activeType, intensity: activeIntensity }];

It must be:

return [...filtered, { zone: activeZone, type: activeType, intensity: activeIntensity }];

4. localStorage keys

Replace smart quotes:

const saved = localStorage.getItem("inner_atlas_v1");
localStorage.setItem("inner_atlas_v1", JSON.stringify(snapshots));

5. Timeline/map view strings

Use plain strings:

const [view, setView] = useState("map"); // map | timeline | patterns

6. CSS variable in inline style

This can annoy TypeScript:

style={{ "--pct": `${(activeIntensity - 1) / 9 * 100}%` }}

Safer version:

style={{ ["--pct" as string]: `${((activeIntensity - 1) / 9) * 100}%` }}


